post_text:
Dear Silver Lake Students, Parents, and Community,

We have all become accustomed to the quickly changing landscape of the school and activities environment. We are currently in a situation where there have been a few positive cases of COVID-19 in the district. Due to our requirement to contact trace we are in a situation where the majority of our high school football staff, and possibly some high school football athletes will need to quarantine following the KDHE guidelines.

If your high school football athlete needs to quarantine you will be notified tomorrow.

This will require us to postpone our high school football season for the next two weeks and focus on making sure we are all healthy and ready to return to the field safely for the remainder of the season.

All other fall activities will continue as scheduled.

We continue to monitor all students and coaching/teaching staff very closely and at this time we are not aware of any new cases in the district.

Thank You,

post_text:
8th Grade Promotion Announcements/Reminders,

Students who will be participating in the 8th-grade promotion ceremony on Monday, July 27th, at 7 PM need to be at the school on Monday morning by 8:00 am for a quick practice walkthrough of the ceremony.
We will initially meet in the commons area/PAC for quick instructions and to watch the 8th-grade class video. Make sure you are wearing a mask when you arrive. If you do not have a mask we will provide a disposable one for you.
We will then go outside to practice the ceremony.
We hope to be done between 9:15 - 9:30.

Parents, your student will be bringing home multiple copies of the program that is normally handed out at the door. Please hand those out to your family and friends as we will not setting any out at the ceremony Monday evening.

2020 Seniors,
The following is a list of reminders and announcements related to graduation this weekend.

Friday, July 24th.
All seniors who are participating in graduation need to be in the new gym by 9:45 for our 10:00 graduation practice.
As a class, we will watch the senior video before going outside for practice (the video will be posted on the website so others can view it later).

Saturday, July 25th.
Seniors park in the front parking lot (south side) or as close to Lake St. as possible.
Be in the new gym no later than 10:30 (doors will open at 9:30).
There will not be a receiving line.

post_text:
2020 High School Commencement Ceremony Re-Scheduled.

Given the restrictions we are currently operating under there is no possible way to hold Graduation ceremonies in May unless it was done virtually. We are cautiously optimistic that by moving Graduation for the class of 2020 to Saturday, July 25th, at 11:00 AM, it will increase the likelihood that some of the social gathering restrictions will be relaxed and we will be able to hold Graduation ceremonies. While we hope that those ceremonies are more traditional in nature, we must be prepared to adjust the ceremonies to meet any social distancing requirements and crowd size limitations that we are operating under at that time. Considering the Senior class size, the limited staff required to conduct a graduation ceremony, the ability to adjust the location (outside if needed) we are hopeful that gives us the flexibility we need to provide our 2020 Graduates with a ceremony that allows them to experience Graduation together.

USD Parents (9:00 am, Thursday, March 19th)

We have a couple of clarifying pieces of information relative to delivery and pickup of personal belonging.

1. Any student who lives along our normal bus routes will have their items brought to them today via the school bus. This includes all students along the route regardless of whether or not your child typically rides the bus.

2. Regarding larger items such as band instruments, art projects, wood projects, etc. we will do our best to get those ready today but with the short window, we are on we may have to make some of those available in the next week or so, we apologize.

3. We are asking that if you have library books, assignments to be turned into teachers, or other school-owned property we are asking for you to hold on to those items. IF it is a project or assignment that needs to be turned into a teacher we are working on a plan to pick those up on an individual basis.
text:
USD Parents (9:00 am, Thursday, March 19th)

We have a couple of clarifying pieces of information relative to delivery and pickup of personal belonging.

1. Any student who lives along our normal bus routes will have their items brought to them today via the school bus. This includes all students along the route regardless of whether or not your child typically rides the bus.

2. Regarding larger items such as band instruments, art projects, wood projects, etc. we will do our best to get those ready today but with the short window, we are on we may have to make some of those available in the next week or so, we apologize.

3. We are asking that if you have library books, assignments to be turned into teachers, or other school-owned property we are asking for you to hold on to those items. IF it is a project or assignment that needs to be turned into a teacher we are working on a plan to pick those up on an individual basis.

post_text:
Taken from the post of Sheriff Brian C. Hill.

Sheriff Hill announces that the Shawnee County Sheriff's Office will be increasing traffic enforcement efforts around the Shawnee County area high schools as part of the SAFE (Seatbelts Are For Everyone) program initiative. The enforcement phase will be Feb 24th ‚Äì March 6th. Officers will be focusing efforts on seat belt compliance.

This is the tenth year that the Sheriff‚Äôs Office has participated in the SAFE program. Throughout the 2019-20 school year, the Sheriff‚Äôs Office has again partnered with the Kansas Traffic Safety Resource Office (KSRTO) to provide public information and education to help protect students from avoidable injury or death on Shawnee County roadways. School Resource Officers have been working with students at Silver Lake, Rossville, Shawnee Heights, Seaman, and Washburn Rural to bring awareness to the importance of wearing a seat belt.
